 with authorization2star  aFor the better understanding of the cultural and linguistic impact of colonialism on the shaping of the world as we know it today it is necessary to take account of the Europeanization of the map of the extra-European countries.To achieve this goal Comparative Colonial Toponomastics (CoCoTop) investigates the place names which were coined in the era of colonialism in the erstwhile possessions of European colonizer nations. This edited volume offers new insights into the toponomastic manifestations of Danish, French, German, Italian, and Spanish colonialism. The focus is on hitherto unexplored macrotoponyms and microtoponyms. Their structural and functional aspects are described. They are linked to the colonial history of the various nations involved. A general toponomastic framework beyond CoCoTop is presented additionally. Several of the papers mark the starting point of recently initiated new research projects.The volume is of special interest to onomasticians, scholars working in colonial and postcolonial linguistics, and historians of colonialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aNames, Geographical. 0aToponymy. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Historical & Comparative.2bisacsh  aColonial Linguistics.  aColonial Toponomastics.  aPostcolonial Studies.1 aBlom, Jascha de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aContini, Riccardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrandjean Gøgsig Jakobsen, Johnny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerling, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKühl, Karoline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevkovych, Nataliya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela